## 2. Anatomy of a DB schema change

### 2.1 Create a new migration SQL file

Location: `mock_data_v2/database_application_v2/database/`

Naming convention: `schema_<table>_add_<short-description>.sql` (for ADDs)
or `schema_<table>_<description>.sql` (for more general changes).

Examples from the repo:
- `schema_planner_output_add_job_id.sql`
- `schema_solver_jobs_add_plan_range.sql`
- `schema_solver_jobs_add_fetch_flags.sql`
- `schema_planner_assignments_add_category_priority.sql`

Template:
```sql
-- Fix #NN (YYYY-MM-DD) — short description of what and why.
-- Idempotent via IF NOT EXISTS / ON CONFLICT. Safe to re-run.

ALTER TABLE <table>
    ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS <col> <type> [DEFAULT <value>] [NOT NULL];

COMMENT ON COLUMN <table>.<col> IS 'what this column means + when to read it';

CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_<table>_<col> ON <table>(<col>);
```

### 2.2 Wire into the postgres Dockerfile (fresh-install path)

Edit `mock_data_v2/database_application_v2/docker/Dockerfile.postgres`.
Insert a `COPY` line in the appropriate numbered position — before
`init-db.sh` (which is always last in alphabetical order).

```dockerfile
COPY ../database/schema_<your_new_file>.sql /docker-entrypoint-initdb.d/NN-schema-<your-name>.sql
```

Renumber `init-db.sh` to stay last if needed:
```dockerfile
COPY ../database/init-db.sh /docker-entrypoint-initdb.d/<last-number>-init-db.sh
RUN chmod +x /docker-entrypoint-initdb.d/<last-number>-init-db.sh
```

### 2.3 Wire into `local_deploy.sh` (existing-volume path)

Edit `mock_data_v2/database_application_v2/local_deploy.sh`, inside the
`apply_migrations()` function. Append to the `MIGRATIONS` array:

```bash
local MIGRATIONS=(
    "./database/schema_replannable_demand_types.sql"                   # Fix #7
    "./database/schema_solver_jobs_add_fetch_flags.sql"                # Fix #16
    "./database/schema_planner_assignments_add_category_priority.sql"  # Fix #16
    "./database/schema_<your_new_file>.sql"                            # Fix #NN
)
```

The deploy script applies them in array order using
`docker exec -i <pg_container> sh -c 'psql -v ON_ERROR_STOP=1 -U "$POSTGRES_USER" -d "$POSTGRES_DB"' < <sql>`.

Order matters if migrations have dependencies (e.g., adding a column
that's referenced by a later ALTER). When in doubt, put dependency
chains in alphanumeric order and verify locally.

### 2.4 Verify on QA before UAT/PROD

```bash
cd mock_data_v2/database_application_v2

# Apply to QA via the script
./local_deploy.sh -qa

# Confirm the column/index/etc. exists
docker exec cff_postgres_qa psql -U cff_app_user -d cff_planning \
    -c "\d <table>"

# Re-run the deploy script — should be a NO-OP
./local_deploy.sh -qa
# Expect: `NOTICE: column "<col>" of relation "<table>" already exists, skipping`
```

The re-run being a no-op is the acceptance criterion. If the migration
fails on re-run, it's not idempotent — fix before moving on.

