## 3. Anatomy of a backend router change

When the schema change requires a new column to surface in an endpoint:

### 3.1 Update SELECT statements

Edit `mock_data_v2/database_application_v2/api/routers/<router>.py`.

**Always update the LIST endpoint AND the single-item endpoint.** It's
common to miss one and produce inconsistent responses.

```python
query = text("""
    SELECT
        existing_col_a, existing_col_b,
        <new_col>,          -- Fix #NN
        more_existing_cols
    FROM <table>
    WHERE ...
""")
```

### 3.2 Update INSERT / UPDATE paths

For INSERT: add the column to the INSERT column list and the VALUES
clause. Pass the new value in the params dict.

For UPDATE: conditional-append pattern (only update when the new value
is supplied):
```python
if new_col_value is not None:
    update_fields.append("<new_col> = :<new_col>")
    params["<new_col>"] = new_col_value
```

This prevents stale payloads from overwriting existing values with None.

### 3.3 Default values for pre-existing rows

Rows that existed before the column was added will have either `NULL`
(if no DEFAULT) or the DEFAULT value. Document which is expected in the
deployment notes and the migration SQL comment.

Example: `solver_jobs.fetch_rt` has `DEFAULT TRUE`. Rows that existed
before Fix #16 show `true`. New rows get the actual payload-derived
value. FE should tolerate both without special-casing.

