## 5. Things to avoid

### 5.1 Destructive defaults

Never make a deploy command drop data unless explicitly flagged. The
old `local_deploy.sh` did `down -v` + `clean_pgdata` unconditionally
— this caused data loss on every deploy. Fix #pre-16 corrected this by
making `--wipe` an opt-in flag.

### 5.2 Non-idempotent migrations

Bare `ALTER TABLE ... ADD COLUMN` (without `IF NOT EXISTS`) fails on
re-run. Always include the guard.

Likewise, `INSERT INTO <seed>` without `ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING` or
`WHERE NOT EXISTS` will duplicate rows on re-run.

### 5.3 Schema drift between fresh and existing deployments

If you add a new column to a table in the schema file (`schema.sql`) but
forget the corresponding `ALTER ... IF NOT EXISTS` migration, fresh
deploys get the column but existing volumes don't. This is the single
most common cause of "it works on my machine" on this project.

**Rule**: every column in a base schema file must have an equivalent
idempotent migration file that covers existing volumes.

### 5.4 Forgetting the `local_deploy.sh` MIGRATIONS array

It's easy to drop a new `.sql` file into `database/` and wire it into
the Dockerfile without also adding it to the deploy script's
`MIGRATIONS` array. Fresh installs pick it up; existing volumes don't.
Always update both.

